column168: DRIVER WAS PARKED AT STOP NOS OF A 9 STOP PEDDLE.  NOTICED LUQID DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER DOOR.  CALLED HIS DISPATCHER, RECEIVING CLERK CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. DRIVER CALLED BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND ADVISED THERE WAS THE APPEARANCE OF SMOKE AND COULD NOT/WOULD NOT OPEN TRAILER DOOR. WAS TOLD TO CONTAIN LEAK SO LIQUID WOULD NOT CONTINUE TO FLOW INTO THE SEWER.  HE DID SO.  THE SERVICE CTR MGR FOR THE CARRIER, CALLED THE SHIPPER, THE OFFICE MGR THE PRIVATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT EVENTUALLY CALLED IN 5 OTHER FIRE DEPTS AND THE DEPT OF PUBLIC WORKS.  ALL WERE IN SOME WAY PART OF THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP. THIS FINALLY BEGAN APPROX 4 HOURS AFETER THE INITIAL CALL BY THE DRIVER EVEN THOUGHT ALL WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 2 HRS.  ONE PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM OF ONE TOTAL SHPPED WAS TRANSPORTED ON A PALLET WITHOUT BEING SECURED TO THE PALLET.  WHEN THE TRLR WAS PLACED TO THE DOCK, THE APRON BEING A CANTED PIT, THE DRUM FELL AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT AND SUSTAINED A PUNCTURE OF APPROX 2 1/2" X 2 1/2".  BY THE TIM ECLEANUP AND CONTAINMENT HAD BEGUN, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS HAD DRAINED FROM THE DRUM.  ALTHOUGH INSTRUCTIONS ARE CLEARLY KNOWN TO ALL EMPLOYEES- FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WILL BE BLOCKED REGARDLESS OF THE ROADWORTHNESS OF THE PACKAGING.  THE SHIPPERS WILL BE MADE AWARE OF THIER RESPONSIBLITY TO TENDER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN A MANNER THAT WILL ASSURE SAFE TRANSPORT.

THE CARDBOARD CARTON HAD ABSORBED THE SPILLAGE.  SEVERAL OTHER CARTONS WERE DAMP BUT NOTHING WAS DAMAGED.  CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE PRODUCT.

OUR DRIVER FAILED TO PLACE A PAIL UNDER THE CONNECTION AND IN THE PROCESS SPILLED APPROX. 20 GALLONS ON THE GROUND. OUR DRIVER WAS COUNSELED, AND ADVISED THAT IN THE FUTURE HE SHOULD ALWAYS HAVE A PAIL UNDER ALL CONNECTIONS, TO AVOID THIS HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THIS INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED AT 0830, FEBRUARY 21, 1993. THIS INCIDENT WAS DUE TOTHE CORROSIVE EFFECTS OF THE MATERIAL ON THE METAL OF THE STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.THE FAILED OVERPACK DRUM SHOWED SIGNS OF NEGLECT ALTHOUGH ALL OTHER OVERPACKSIN THE SHIPMENT LOOKED TO BE IN VERY GOOD CONDITION. OUR CREW REMOVED THEORIGINAL DRUM FROM THE LEAKING OVERPACK AND PLACED IT INTO A POLY OVERPACK. ALLSPILLED MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER WAS ABSORBED. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OFMATERIAL HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL AND ABSORBENTMATERIALS WERE PLACED IN TWO STELL OVERPACKS. ALTHOUGH OUR VANS HAVE AFIBERGLASS CONTAINMENT PAN, THIS PAN HAD A CRACK IN THE FLOOR TO SIDE SEEMWHICH ALLOWED THE MATERIALS OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THIS TRAILER WILL BEREPAIRED AND UPGRADED IN THE SEAM AREA WITH A PROCESS WE HAVE FOUND TO BE FARSUPERIOR TO THE ORIGINAL SEAM WELD BEING USED BY THE CONTAINMENT PANMANUFACTURER. THE MATERIAL WILL BE DELIVERED TO THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE/DISPOSALFACILITY.

OF APPROX. 10 GALLONS LEAKED FROM THE REAR (4TH) COMPARTMENT, RAN DOWN THE INSIDE OF THE SPILL DAM RAILING, AND ESCAPED DOWN THE LEFT FRONT TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND. DRIVER WAS OPERATING THE TRUCK AT APPROX. 45 MPH ON A SLIGHT DOWN GRADE WITH A CURVE TO THE RIGHT AT THE BOTTOM OF THE GRADE.  AS DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO NEGOTIATE THE RIGHT CURVE, THE TIRES ON THE EMPTY TRAILER LOST TRACTION AND STARTED TO SLIDE TO THE LEFT.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO COUNTER STEER AND THE TRAILER SWUNG BACK AROUND TO THE RIGHT AND KEPT GOING AROUND FORCING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER INTO THE MEDIAN AND ACROSS THE TWO NORTH BOUND LANES WHERE THE TRUCK LAID OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE FACING NORTH ON THE BERM OF THE ROAD.  THERE WERE NO INJURIED OR RELEASE OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, BUT RT 23 WAS CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS FOR ABOUT 5 HOURS WHILE THEY UPRIGHTED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER.

THE RECEIVER CLOSED HIS VALVE BEFORE THE HOSE WAS EMPTY AND THIS IS WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION.  HE PROCEEDED TO OPEN HIS NTERNAL VALVE IN ORDER TO OBTAIN A SAMPLE FOR THE CUSTOMER. OUR DRIVER CLOSED THE INTERNAL IMMEDIATELY AND IN CHECKING FOUND THAT WHOEVER CLEANED THE TRAILER FAILED TO REINSTALL THE PACKING NUT ON THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE, OUR DRIVER ISTALLED A PACKING NUT AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD SULFURIC ACID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF UNIT 31501. THE PRODUCT SPRAYED ONTO THE FOLLOWING CAR DRIVEN BY MR. ED JONES. MR. JONES STOPPED OUR TRUCK AND AFTER INVESTIGATION, OUR DRIVER INFORMED MR. JONES THAT SULFURIC ACID WAS ON HIS CAR. HE ADVISE MR. JONES THAT HE SHOULD IMMEDIATELY WASH HIS CAR IN THE CAR WASH. HE THEN GAVE MR. JONES MY NAME & NUMBER TO WORK OUT THE INSURANCE AND THE DETAILS ON REPAIRING HIS CAR. APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF SULFURIC HAD SPILLED FROM OUR CONTAINER DURING TRANSPORT FROM NAS-JACKSONVILLE TO THE SITE OF THE INCIDENT. AFTER DISCUSSING THIS WITH JOHN WILSON, I FOUND OUT THAT THERE WERE FOUR (4) 15 GALLON DELDRUMS OF SULFURIC ACID ON A SKID SECURED ONLY BY SHRINKWRAP.JOHNNIE REPORTED THAT WHEN HE LEFT NAS-JACKSONVILLE, (PREVIOUS DELIVERY), A VEHICLE PULLED OUT IN FROM OF HIM CAUSING HIM TO HIT HIS BRAKES VERY HARD. HE FEELS THAT THIS IS THE POINT WHERE THE DRUMS OVERTURNED. HOWEVER, JOHNNIE DID NOT CHECK TO SEE IF THE LOAD WAS STILL SECURE. I EXPLAINED THAT EVERY ITEM ON OUR TRUCKS MUST BE SECURED BY EITHER LOAD BARS OR STRAPS AND THE SHRINKWRAP IS NOT EVER SUFFICIENT. ALSO AFTER ANY SUDDEN MOVEMENT, YOU ARE REQUIRED TO STOP AND CHECK TO ENSURE THAT THE LOAD IS STILL SECURED.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE, THE DRIVER LEFT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, TO GETHIS COFFEE AND SANDWICH OUT OF THE CAB OF THE TRUCK. WHEN HE RETURNED TO THEREAR OF THE TRAILER THE OIL WAS OVER FLOWING THE TANK, HE WAS DROPPING HIS LOADINTO. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVES STOPPING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.THEN THE DRIVER NOTIFIED OUR DISPATCH, AND THE DISPATCH NOTIFIED OUR EMERGENCYRESPONSE TEAM, TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN SUSPENDED FORVIOLATING COMPANY POLICY, (DRIVERS ARE NOT TO LEAVE REAR OF TRAILER WHILE INTHE UNLOADING PROCESS). ALSO I HAVE SENT A MEMO OUT TO THE REST OF OUR DRIVERSTO REMIND THEM THAT ALL COMPANY POLICIES MUST BE FOLLOWED, TO PREVENT THIS FROMHAPPENIING AGAIN.

column168: A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER CONTAINING PLATING SLUDGE WASTE CONTAMINATED WITH VARIOUS HEAVY METALS WAS EN ROUTE TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT'S EMELLE FACILITY LOCATED IN EMELLE, AL FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE BRAINTREE, MA 02184 ON 2/22/93. UPON EXIT FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. THE LOAD WAS CHECKED AND NO FREE LIQUIDS WERE PRESENT. A LAYER OF SPEEDI DRY WAS ALSO PLACED AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER IN THE EVENT SNOW, ICE OR RAIN GOT INTO THE CONTAINER. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE REAR PORTION OF THE CONTAINER. HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED POLY SHEETS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL UNDER THE VEHICLE AND CALLED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. A FIELD SERVICE CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM THE CLEAN HARBOR'S BALTIMORE, MD SERVICE CENTER. ALSO NOTIFIED WAS THE COUNTY OF SHENANDOAH'S FIRE MARSHAL'S OFFICE, WHO SUBSEQUENTLY SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE TO OBSERVE. NO ASSISTANCE FROM THE FIRE MARSHAL'S OFFICE WAS REQUIRED. UPON ARRIVAL THE CREW, ALONG WITH THE DRIVER, CLEANED UP THE MATERIAL THAT HAD ESCAPED. ADDITIONAL SPEEDI DRY WAS ADDED TO THE LOAD TO ABSORB ANY RESIDUAL MOISTURE AND SECURED THE LOAD RELEASE WAS PLACED IN THE CONTAINER AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE ORIGINAL WASTE  MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ABSORBENT MATERIAL WILL BE ADDED TO THE DOORS AND CORNERS OF EACH ROLL-OFF CONTAINER TO ACT AS A BARRIER AGAINST ANY MOISTURE THAT MAY ACCUMULATE AFTER LOADING IS COMPLETED BY THE SHIPPER.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION AND HOOKED UP TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE. AS HE STARTED THE TRANSFER ONE OF THE FITTINGS HE USED TO ACCOMPLISH HIS HOOK UP STARTED TO LEAK. HE SHUT DOWN AND NOTIFIED THE RECEIVER. IN CHECKING HE FOUND THAT HE HAD USED A DISCOLORED BRASS FITTING THAT HE THOUGHT WAS STAINLESS STEEL AND THE MATERIAL CORRODED THE METAL ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO LEAK. HE CHANGED TO THE PROPER TYPE FITTING AND COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY. THE CUSTOMER TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.

OUT DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY. HE MADE HIS HOOKUP AND STARTED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE. IN CHECKING THE PROCESS HE NOTED THAT A HOSE BELONGING TO THE CUSTOMER WAS LEAKING. HE SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY AND HE THE RECEIVER NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND CLEANED IT UP. THE HOSE WAS SWITCHED AND THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO DELIVER AND HAD STOPPED IN A REST AREA TO TAKE A BREAK. HE WAS AWAKENED BY ANOTHER DRIVER AND ADVISED THAT PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS TERMINAL AND THE AUTHORITIES. A CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO CATCH THE MATERIAL. ANOTHER TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED FROM OUR CLOSEST TERMINAL AND THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED WHILE THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT STOOD BY. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR PERSONNEL THAT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.

WHILE UNLOADING THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER, THE FITTING BEING USED FAILED CAUSING THE DISCHARGE OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE VALVE WAS COLSED IMMEDIATELY AND DISPATCH WAS NOTIFIED. ANOTHER FITTING AND MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WAS SENT TO THE CUSTOMERS LOCATION. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP. A FOLLOWUP INSPECTION ON 3/23/93 VERIFIED THAT EVERYTHING WAS COMPLETED AS REQUIRED.

column168: ON DATE AND TIME INDICATED ABOVE THE SOUND OF ESCAPING GAS WAS DETECTED COMING FROM CAR AT ILLINOIS CENTRAL TRAINYARD. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND CAR WAS ISOLATED TO A HOLDING TRACK. column168: DRIVER WAS AT A MUSKET CONVENIENCE STORE UNLOADING UNLEADED GASOLINE AND HAD FILLED ONE TANK AND WAS FILLING ANOTHER TANK - UNAWARE THE TWO TANKS WERE PIPED TOGETHER. DRIVERS WERE EN ROUTE FRON SARNIA, CANADA TO DELAWARE CITY, AFTER PICKING UP A FULLY LOADED TRAILER.  WHILE EN ROUTE, THEY NOTICED PRODUCT VENTING FROM THE VENT STACK.  THEY IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE NEAR EAST PETERSBURG, PENNSYLVANIA, TO INVESTIGATE AND DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER VESSEL PRESSURE HAD RISEN TO 54 PSIG.  AFTER CONSULTATION WITH SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL, THE TRAILER WAS DIRECTED TO A NEARBY CUSTOMER IN EAST PETERSBURG AND STABILIZED TO 6 PSIG.  THE TRAILER CONTINUED ON TO DELAWARE CITY WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AN INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE TRAILER WAS INITIALLY OVERLOADED IN SARNIA, CANADA.  AT TIME OF LOADING, THE TRAILER WAS COVERED WITH AN ACCUMULATION OF ICE AND SNOW.  THE CALCULATIONS TO COMPENSATE FOR THIS EXTRA WEIGHT WERE NOT ACCURATE WHICH CAUSED OVERLOADING OF PRODUCT.  ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REINSTRUCTED NOT TO LEAVE THE TERMINALS IF THE TRAILER WEIGHT EXCEEDS THE MAXIMUM LOADED WEIGHT.

ETC DRIVER HAD UNLOADED APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS INTO ARMCO INC. STORAGE TANK.  AS THEIR STORAGE TANK COULD NOT HOLD THE 500 TOTAL GALLONS FROM HIS COMPARTMENT, THE PLANT BROUGHT ANOTHER SMALL TANK TO PUT THE OTHER 100 GALLONS INTO.  THEY PUT THE TANK UP AGAINST THE PLATFORM THAT GOES INTO THE BUILDING WHERE YOU COULD NOT SEE THE BACK SIDE OF TANK.  OUR DRIVER WAS TOLD TO GO AHEAD AND UNLOAD THE 100 GALLONS INTO THIS TANK, WHICH HE DID.  WHEN HE WALKED OVER TO THE SMALL TANK, TO TAKE THE HOSE OUT HE NOTICED CHEMICAL ON GROUND.  THERE WAS NO VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF THE SMALL TANK, SO APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT RAN OUT.  BAKER PERFORMANCE EMPLOYEE MR. TOM EBERT WAS PRESENT.  THEY STOPPED LEAK AND CLEANED UP SPILL.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED ON TWILIGHT SORT 2/3/93 AT ABOUT 8:30PM.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS LOCATED AT PD-4, WHEN I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE THE DAMAGED PACKAGE HAD ALREADY BEEN PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG.  I THEN PROCEEDED TO PUT IT IN A BLACK SPILL TOTE FOR TRANSPORTAION TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCESSING AREA.  THE LOADER HANDLING THE PACKAGE HAD SPILLAGE ON HIS JEANS AND T-SHIRT.  AFTER CONTACTING CHEMTREC THEY SUGGESTED FOR THE LOADER TO REMOVE HIS CLOTHING AND THAT THEY BE DISPOSED OF.  AFTER RETREIVING THE LOADER'S CLOTHING, I THEN PROCEEDED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCESSING AREA.   DOING AS CHEMTREC SUGGESTED, I PUT ON THE SCBA GEAR AND PROCEEDED TO EXAMINE THE PACKAGE.  ON DOING SO, IT WAS REVEALED THAT THE 4 BOTTLES HAD LOOSE CAPS.  THE CAPS WRE TIGHTENED AND THE 4 BOTTLES WERE REPACKED AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE CARDBOARD AND CLOTHING WERE DISPOSED OF IN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURE.

PREVIOUS TO SHIPPING, CAR GATX 301055 HAD A NEW VALVE ON DOME INSTALLED BY SHIPPER.  AS TEMPERATURES ROSE PRESSURE BUILT UP IN CAR CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID TO ESCAPE AND COLLECT ON TOP OF SNOW COVERED TANK CAR. DUE TO THE WARM TEMPERATURE, THE SNOW ON TOP WAS MELTING AND THIS WAS THOUGHT TO BE THE DRIPPING LIQUID.  AS A PRECAUTION, GE WAS NOTIFIED AND CAR INSPECTED.  INSPECTION REVEALED FOUR (4) BOLTS ON DOME HAD NOT BEEN TIGHTENED BY THE SHIPPER.  UPON TIGHTENING OF BOLTS, DRIPPING STOPPED. D&H SUPERVISOR WAS NOT MADE AWARE OF ACTUAL LOSS OF METHANOL AT TIME OF INCIDENT.  SNOW MELT WAS THOUGHT TO BE DRIPPING LIQUID THAT HAD ESCAPED AND COLLECTED ON TOP OF CAR.

SWITCH CREW NOTED CAR SUNX 26844 LEAKING DURING COUPLING OPERATION.  MGR MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, H.G. WITT, INSPECTED CAR AND DETERMINED LIQUID COMING FROM UNDER A FLANGE ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE FLANGE IS WHERE THE LIQUID LINE, AIR LINE, VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, AND SAMPLE LINE ARE MOUNTED. THE GASKET UNDER THE FLANGE HAD FAILED WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO LEAK WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE GAP WAS PLUGGED WITH TEFLON PACKING MATERIAL AND CAULKED WITH SILICONE.  CAR WAS MOVED TO CONSIGNEE IN FREEPORT, TX WITHOUT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MGR G. B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT RUSX 3016 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  MGR REEDER RESPONDED AND OBSERVED LIQUID ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR THAT HAD COME FROM THE AREA AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  INSPECTION OF THE HOUSING DETERMINED THAT THE HANDLE ON THE AIR LINE WOULD NOT CLEAR THE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE.  WHEN THE AIR VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE HANDLE HELD THE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE OPEN. CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: BATTERIES WHER SHRINK WRAPPED ON PALLETS AND THE VIBRATION OF THE TRUCK CAUSED THE PALLET TO CRACK, LETTING THE BATTERIES FALL OVER. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE BATTERIES. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED SPILL PROCEDURES. UPON OUR ARRIVAL AT THE SITE, WHICH WAS A REST AREA OFF I-85 NORTH AT OR ABOUT MILE MARKER 195, WE SPOKE WITH THE DRIVER, JAY SCHARFENBERG, AND MADE AN INITIAL ASSESMENT OF THE SITUATION. JAY HAD DON AN EXCELLENT JOB CONTAINING THE SPILL WITH AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK AND OIL DRY. AFTER DETERMINING AND CONFIRMING EITH THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES THAT THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE OR IMMEDIATE DANGER WE PREPARED FOR ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER TO ASSESS THE CONDITION OF THE MATERIALS BEING TRANSPORTED. THIRTY TO FORTY-FIVE MINUTES AFTER OUR ARRIVAL AT THE SITE CHRIS HART ARRIVED WITH A TRACTOR TRAILER AND ADDITIONAL SUPPLIES. HE BACKED HIS TRAILER SO THAT IT WAS END TO END WITH JAY'S TRAILER WHICH ALLOWED US CONVENIENT ACCESS OT OUR SUPPLIES. CHRIS AND I DONNED PPE CONSISTING OF YELLOW TYVEKS, NITRILE GLOVES, POLY BOOTS, AND SCBA AND ENTERED THE TRAILER. WE FOUND SEVERAL LARGE, INDUSTRIAL SIZE STATIONARY, LEAD ACID BATTERIES LEAKING DUE TO CRACKED PLASTIC CASINGS WHICH ACTED AS THE RESERVOIR FOR THE SULFURIC ACID ELECTROLYTE. THE LEAKS APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY A COMBINATION OF FACTORS  INCLUDING: THE POOR CONDITION OF SOM OF THE BATTERIES IMPROPER LOADING OF THE TRUCK, POOR PALLET. SELECTION AND THE FAILURE OF PROPERLY SECURE THE LOAD. BY THE TIME WE HAD THE OPPORTUNITY OT INSPECT THE LEAKING OUT INTO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRUCK. ADDITIONAL OIL DRY WAS SPREAD TO ABSORB ALL MATERIAL POSSIBLE AND A PLAN TO OVERPACK THE BATTERIES IN A MANNER TO MINIMIZE THE RISK OF INJURY TO THE INVOLVED PERSONNEL OR ADDITIONAL RELEASED OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS DEVELOPED AND IMPLEMENTED.

column168: THE PACKAGE HAD SOME THING HEAVY RESTING ON IT, WHICH CAUSED 3 BOTTLES TO GET CRUSHED, OUT OF THE 11 IN THE BOX.

AGENT/HAZMAT, C.E. ZERWECK, WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER MATU 225323 WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY WHILE BEING PLACED ON THE RAMP AT THE MESQUITE FACILITY. AGENT ZERWECK RESPONDED AND OBSERVED AN AREA 6' FROM THE DOORS OF THE CONTAINER THAT WAS WET.  BLOCKING AND BRACING APPEARED TO BE GOOD AND INTACT.  AGENT ZERWECK CONTACTED NORMAN CHENG OF UNITEK ENVIRONMENTAL SYSTEMS AND ADVISED HIM OF THE SITUATION.  MR. CHENG RETAINED EMTECH TO RESPOND AND REMEDIATE.  EMTECH'S INSPECTION DETERMINED (CHIP DAY) THAT THREE DRUMS WERE CORRODED AND HAD FAILED.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE LOADED FOR DISPOSAL.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

column42: POISONOUS LIQUIDS, N.O.S. INHALATION HAZARD, PACKING GROUP I, ZONE B
column168: STATEMENT BY KENNETH SPRITZER, I/B WORKING FOREMAN: WHEN I WENT TO UNLOAD TRLR.  19-B214, AS I OPENED THE DOOR, NOXIOUS FUMES CAME OUT.  I WAITED APPROX. 2 HRS FOR THE FUMES TO DISSIPATE AND THEN TOOK CTN OFF THE TRLR WHICH WAS LABELES POISON AND PUT IT OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING. ENVIRONMENTAL PRODS. AND SERVICES WAS CALLED AND THEY CAME OUT IMMEDIATELY AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT OF POISON IN AN OVERPACK DRUM FOR THEM TO DISPOSE OF AT A LATER DATE.  THE DRUM OF MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL HAS BEEN PROFILED INTO A FEDERALLY LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY AND WILL BE TRANSPORTED WHEN THE PROFILE IS APPROVED.
